    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "Wait, what do you mean by \"leafy goblin\"? I'm just talking about my tomato plants. Can we get back to the soil? How do I check if the pH is the problem or if it's definitely just the nitrogen?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Oh, sorry about that! I got a little carried away with the goblin imagery, but I promise I'm not trying to turn your tomatoes into a goblin army. You're right, let's get back to the serious business of soil and pH.\n\nTo check if it's pH or nitrogen, you can start by testing the soil with a kit or a digital meter. If the pH is too low (acidic), it can lock up nutrients like nitrogen, making them unavailable to the plant even if they're in the ground. If the pH is too high (alkaline), it can also cause issues, though nitrogen deficiency is usually the first suspect with those yellowing bottom leaves.\n\nYou can also look at the leaves more closely. Nitrogen deficiency often shows as a uniform yellowing starting from the oldest leaves, while pH issues might affect specific nutrients differently. If you're unsure, a soil test is the best way to get a clear answer.\n\nJust remember, even if you fix the soil, you might want to consider adding a little compost or a balanced fertilizer to boost the nitrogen levels. It's always good to have a backup plan, especially when dealing with tricky garden problems.\n\nAnd hey, if you ever find",
